quran[5]{c,v,t,f}:
  10,21,"And when We make mankind taste mercy after some adversity has touched them, there they are with a scheme against Our signs. Say<sup>sg </sup>, “Allah is Swifter in scheming.” Our messengers are indeed writing down what you<sup>pl </sup>scheme{1}.",footnotes:1:Qira’at: Rouh read it as: “…what they scheme.”
  10,22,"It is He Who transports{1}you<sup>pl </sup>across land and sea until, when you are on ships, sailing in a good wind and they{2}rejoice in it, a stormy wind arrives and the waves surge over them from every side and they realize that they are besieged—thereupon they call upon Allah, devoting religion to Him: “If You save us from this, we will most surely be of the thankful.”",footnotes:1:[Qira’at: Ibn Amer and Abu Ja’far read it as: “It is He Who scatters you<sup>pl</sup>…”],footnotes:2:[A grammatical shift in from 2<sup>nd</sup> person to 3 person to 3<sup>rd</sup> person. person.]
  10,23,"But when He has saved them, there they are, committing unjustified aggression in the land. O mankind, your<sup>pl </sup>oppression is only against yourselves—<i>(you only enjoy) </i>{1}the enjoyment of the Earlier Life, then to Us is your<sup>pl </sup>return and We will inform you<sup>pl </sup>of what you used to do.",footnotes:1:Qira’at: All except Hafs read it as: “O mankind, your oppression against yourselves is (only) the enjoyment of the Earlier Life,”
  10,24,"Indeed, the parable of the Earlier Life is but like water that We sent down from the sky, then it was absorbed by the plants of the earth—from which mankind and cattle eat—until, when the earth has put on its decorations and is adorned and its inhabitants think that they have mastered it, Our command comes upon it by night or by day and We turn it into stubble, as if it had not flourished the day before. Thus We detail the signs for people who reflect."
  10,25,"And Allah invites to the Home of Peace and guides whomever He wills to a straight path."
